Wrangle with data.table

Data wrangling is one of the most important skills in data science and statistical programming. The data.table data structure in R is a tabular structure organising data into rows and columns, just like a data.frame. Unlike a data.frame, a data.table is a feature-rich and efficient data structure. This short guide to data wrangling with data.table will equip you with the basic understanding and skills to start using data.tables for data wrangling and more.

Getting Started

Before you can use the data.table structure, you will need to install the data.table package to your machine and load it into your session. The data.table package make the data.table class available, and brings with it a host of useful functions.

install.packages("data.table")
library(data.table)

Creating data.tables

There are three main ways you will get data into data.tables. If you want to read in an external data file which is where most of the key data we use in an R program comes from use the fread() function. This function reads in external files of a variety of filetypes and from local directories (including zipped directories) and from the internet. The fread() function is fast, versatile and easy to use. File locations and names are passed as a string to the function, just like you would with functions like read.table(), read.csv() or read_delim().

# Read in the flights dataset
flights <- fread("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Rdatatable/data.table/master/vignettes/flights14.csv")

# Return a preview of the flights dataset
flights

The flights dataset is data collected for all flights departing from New York city airports in 2014 it will be used throughout these notes. Two other datasets will be used. The first is dtcars a data.table version of the mtcars dataset. To generate this, use the setDT() function which will convert an existing data.frame, list or tibble into a data.table. Note that built-in datasets cannot have a new class assigned so you first need to make a copy of the mtcars object objects that are generated within the session can be converted without this copying step first. Note we are also specifying the option keep.rownames=TRUE data.tables dont use rownames so if want that information to remain (and its useful information in this case) we can tell R to add a variable called rn.

# Copy mtcars to a new object
dtcars <- copy(mtcars)

# Assign the data.table class to dtcars
setDT(dtcars, keep.rownames=TRUE)

# Return a preview of the dtcars dataset
dtcars

The final way you may want to generate a data.table is to build one by collecting together vectors like you would with the data.frame() function. The data.table() function works in the same way it will construct a data.table from scratch.

# Data on the Nordic sovereign states 
nordics <- data.table(country = c("Denmark", "Finland", "Iceland", "Norway", "Sweden"),
                      iso = c("DNK", "FIN", "ISL", "NOR", "SWE"),
                      eu = c(TRUE, TRUE, FALSE, FALSE, TRUE),
                      pm = c("Frederiksen", "Marin", "Jakobsdttir", "Gahr Stre", "Lfven"),
                      pop_m = c(5.771, 5.623, 0.340, 5.501, 10.130),
                      gdp_b = c(325.556, 252.753, 26.674, 441.439, 554.659),
                      eurovision_wins = c(3L, 1L, 0L, 3L, 6L))

# Return a preview of Nordics
nordics

The data.table notation: dt[i, j, by]

Data.tables are a feature-rich extension of the data.frame structure. To use the features of a data.frame and make the most of its efficiency gains, we can use a notation to describe its standard syntax. The syntax dt[i, j, by] describes:

  • dt - data.table object
  • i - the operations on rows such as sorting or subsetting
  • j - the operations on variables such as selecting or deriving
  • by (and keyby) - grouping variable(s) for the j-operation(s); keyby then sorts the returned data

To demonstrate all four of these elements in a single statement, lets subset the dtcars dataset to observations where cars have over 100 horsepower, then get the mean fuel efficiency for each category of engine cylinder count.

dtcars[hp>100,
       mean(mpg),
       keyby=cyl]
   cyl       V1
1:   4 25.90000
2:   6 19.74286
3:   8 15.10000

This example illustrates some of the key benefits in terms of syntax over data.frames. Focus on the subsetting operation in i to perform the subsetting with a data.frame, we would write mtcars[mtcars$hp>100,]. In other words, with a data.frame we have to repeatedly reference back to the object containing the variables with a data.table we are essentially operating in a micro-environment of variables and we can refer to those variables directly from within the square braces. That means, when we write dtcars[, mpg], R is looking for a variable within dtcars called mpg.

i-operations: sort, sample and subset

j-operations: select, compute and assign
